==Song information==

[[Ray, Goodman & Brown]] recorded "When the Lovin' Goes Out of the Lovin'" for their 1981 album ''Stay''.<ref>(1981) ''Stay'' by Ray, Goodman & Brown [album jacket]. New York: Polydor Records PD-1-6341.</ref>  "[[What's Forever For]]" appeared on the 1978 album ''[[Dr. Heckle & Mr. Jive]]'' by [[England Dan and John Ford Coley]],<ref>(1978) ''[[Dr. Heckle & Mr. Jive]]'' by England Dan and John Ford Coley [album jacket]. New York: Big Tree Records BT 76015.</ref> but [[Michael Martin Murphey]] also released a recording of the song in 1982 that went to number 19 [[Billboard Hot 100|pop]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2009|p=685}}.</ref> and number four [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2007|p=197}}.</ref> and spent a week at number one on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s [[Hot Country Songs|Country]] chart.<ref>{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2002|p=240}}.</ref> "[[Memory (song)|Memory]]" originated in the 1981 Broadway musical ''[[Cats (musical)|Cats]]''<ref name =Friends/> and became a number six hit in the UK for [[Elaine Paige]] that same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search-results-album/_/memory|title= Memory - Singles|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref> And [[Stevie Wonder]]'s "[[Lately (Stevie Wonder song)|Lately]]" reached number three in the UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search-results-album/_/Lately|title=Lately - Singles|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref> and number 29 [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2004|p=636}}.</ref> number 33 [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2007|p=301}}.</ref> and number 64 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2009|p=1075}}.</ref> in the US.

